J	obeidi, amer; hipel, keith william; kilgour, d. marc				Obeidi, Amer; hipel, keith william; Kilgour, D. Marc			Turbulence in Miramichi Bay: The burnt church conflict over native fishing rights	JOURNAL OF THE AMERICAN WATER RESOURCES ASSOCIATION			English	Article; Proceedings Paper	Summer Specialty Conference of the American-Water-Resources-Association	JUN, 2005	Honolulu, HI	Amer Water Resources Assoc		Graph Model for Conflict Resolution; conflict analysis; decision support system; First Nations; fisheries; planning; sustainability; emotion	DECISION-SUPPORT-SYSTEM; WATER-RESOURCES; MODEL	A systematic technique is proposed for assisting in the design and implementation of policy and addressing the need to minimize or resolve disputes that may arise in the enforcement of regulations. The Graph Model for Conflict Resolution is a methodology that facilitates the modeling and analysis of interactive multiple participant-multiple objective decision problems. In the problems considered here, decision makers and policy planners engaged in capacity building typically have different viewpoints over appropriate ways of developing options and enforcing policy choices. Incompatible understandings of resource potentials and limits, and disparities in utilization of these resources, exasperate stakeholders and make the capacity building process counterproductive and even conducive to conflict. A systematic conflict resolution technique is invaluable to policy makers and practitioners in defusing confrontations and reaching out for consensus among participants. In support of current approaches to policy planning and regulation, the Graph Model provides accurate predictions and strategic insights into short- and long-term opportunities in multiple participant-multiple objective decision situations. A conflict among the government of Canada, the Mi'kmaq First Nation, and commercial fishermen over the sharing of a natural resource in New Brunswick, Canada, is used to illustrate the advantages of this technique in practical problems.	Univ Waterloo, Dept Syst Design Engn, Waterloo, ON N2L 3G1, Canada; Wilfrid Laurier Univ, Dept Math, Waterloo, ON N2L 3C5, Canada	obeidi, amer (corresponding author), Univ Waterloo, Dept Syst Design Engn, Waterloo, ON N2L 3G1, Canada.	aaobeidi@uwaterloo.ca					AUGUSTINE RJ, 2002, MIRAMICHI BAY COMMUN; CADDY JF, 2001, CADDY REPORT LOBSTER; Cai XM, 2004, J WATER RES PLAN MAN, V130, P4, DOI 10.1061/(ASCE)0733-9496(2004)130:1(4); Camerer CF, 2003, SCIENCE, V300, P1673, DOI 10.1126/science.1086215; Carraro C., 2005, APPL NEGOTIATION THE; Coates Kenneth., 2000, MARSHALL DECISION NA; COATES KS, 1992, ABORIGINAL LAND CLAI; Costa-Gomes M, 2001, ECONOMETRICA, V69, P1193, DOI 10.1111/1468-0262.00239; *DEP IND AFF NO DE, 2003, REG IND POP SEX RES; Fang L., 1993, INTERACTIVE DECISION; Fang LP, 2003, IEEE T SYST MAN CY C, V33, P42, DOI 10.1109/TSMCC.2003.809361; Fang LP, 2003, IEEE T SYST MAN CY C, V33, P56, DOI 10.1109/TSMCC.2003.809360; Farazmand A., 2004, SOUND GOVERNANCE POL, P1; Fraser N.M., 1984, CONFLICT ANAL MODELS; GLEICK PH, 1993, INT SECURITY, V18, P79, DOI 10.2307/2539033; HARBOE R, 1992, WATER RESOUR BULL, V28, P103; Hipel KW, 1997, APPL MATH COMPUT, V83, P117, DOI 10.1016/S0096-3003(96)00170-1; HIPEL KW, 1992, WATER RESOUR BULL, V28, P3; HIPEL KW, 2007, DECISION SUPPORT SYS; Howard N., 1971, PARADOXES RATIONALIT; Jain SK, 2003, WATER RESOURCES SYST; Johnson EJ, 2002, J ECON THEORY, V104, P16, DOI 10.1006/jeth.2001.2850; Kilgour DM, 2001, GROUP DECIS NEGOT, V10, P159, DOI 10.1023/A:1008713120075; Li KW, 2005, J OPER RES SOC, V56, P699, DOI 10.1057/palgrave.jors.2601870; *LIB ARCH CAN, 2005, ROYAL PROCL 1763; LOUCKS DP, 1995, WATER RESOUR BULL, V31, P571; Lund J. R., 1997, WATER RESOUR UPDATE, V108, P70; Nandalal K. W. D., 2003, STATE OF THE ART SYS; Obeidi A, 2005, GROUP DECIS NEGOT, V14, P481, DOI 10.1007/s10726-005-9004-8; *STAT CAN, 2003, 2001 CENS AN SER AB; THIESSEN EM, 1992, WATER RESOUR BULL, V28, P163; UNDP, 