J	He, SW; kilgour, d. marc; hipel, keith william				He, Shawei; Kilgour, D. Marc; hipel, keith william			A general hierarchical graph model for conflict resolution with application to greenhouse gas emission disputes between USA and China	EUROPEAN JOURNAL OF OPERATIONAL RESEARCH			English	Article						Group decision and negotiation; Hierarchical Graph Model; Greenhouse gas emission; Stability results; Conflict resolutions	CLIMATE-CHANGE NEGOTIATIONS; WATER DIVERSION CONFLICTS; DECISION-SUPPORT-SYSTEM; OPERATIONAL-RESEARCH; GAME-THEORY; STRATEGY; EQUITY	The general hierarchical graph model, a significant expansion of the graph model for conflict resolution methodology, is designed to analyze interrelated conflicts with hierarchical structures. In a general hierarchical graph model, there are common decision makers, who take part in all related subconflicts, and local decision makers, who participate in only one subconflict. In this paper, preference structures for decision makers in a hierarchical graph model are established, and theorems are developed that elucidate the relationship between stabilities in the overall (hierarchical) model and stabilities in the component submodels. To illustrate, the hierarchical graph model is applied to greenhouse gas emission disputes between USA and China, where local decision makers in the USA are the two parties in Congress, and local decision makers in China are state-owned energy companies. The stability results suggest potential strategic resolutions of bilateral disputes, and how parties can attain them. (C) 2016 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.	[He, Shawei] Nanjing Univ Aeronaut & Astronaut, Coll Econ & Management, Nanjing 211106, Jiangsu, Peoples R China; [Kilgour, D. Marc; hipel, keith william] Univ Waterloo, Dept Syst Design Engn, 200 Univ Ave W, Waterloo, ON N2L 3G1, Canada; [Kilgour, D. Marc] Wilfrid Laurier Univ, Dept Math, Waterloo, ON N2L 3C5, Canada; [hipel, keith william] Ctr Int Governance Innovat, Waterloo, O