J	He, SW; kilgour, d. marc; hipel, keith william; Bashar, MA				He, Shawei; Kilgour, D. Marc; hipel, keith william; Bashar, M. Abul			A Basic Hierarchical Graph Model for Conflict Resolution with Application to Water Diversion Conflicts in China	INFOR			English	Article						basic hierarchical model; graph model; conflict resolution; water diversion conflict	STATUS-QUO ANALYSIS; COALITION ANALYSIS; MANAGEMENT; GAMES; TRANSFORMATION; EQUILIBRIA	A basic hierarchical graph model with three decision makers is developed and used to analyze a water diversion conflict in China. This hierarchical graph model combines two component graph models. The theoretical framework of the combined model is constructed using the decision makers, states, moves, and preference structures from the component models. Theorems are developed to relate stable states in the hierarchical model to stable states in local graph models. This novel approach can avoid direct calculation for four hierarchical stabilities. This methodology is applied to a water diversion conflict in China, consisting of conflicts at two locations where it is proposed to divert water from the south to the north of the country. The analytical results show how decision makers can obtain strategic resolutions for the entire conflict.	[He, Shawei; hipel, keith william; Bashar, M. Abul] Univ Waterloo, Dept Syst Design Engn, Waterloo, ON N2L 3G1, Canada; [Kilgour, D. Marc] Wilfrid Laurier Univ, Dept Math, Waterloo, ON N2L 3C5, Canada; [hipel, keith william] Ctr Int Governance Innovat, Waterloo, ON N2L 6C2, Canada	He, SW (corresponding author), Univ Waterloo, Dept Syst Design Engn, Waterloo, ON N2L 3G1, Canada.	s27he@uwaterloo.ca; mkilgour@wlu.ca; kwhipel@uwaterloo.ca; mabashar71@gmail.com					Beimel A, 2008, SIAM J DISCRETE MATH, V22, P360, DOI 10.1137/S0895480104445654; Ben Abdelaziz F, 2004, INFOR, V42, P201; BRAMS SJ, 1981, CONFLICT MANAG PEACE, V6, P39, DOI 10.1177/073889428100600103; Busatto G, 2005, MATH STRUCT COMP SCI, V