J	Xu, HY; hipel, keith william; kilgour, d. marc; Chen, Y				Xu, Haiyan; hipel, keith william; Kilgour, D. Marc; Chen, Ye			Combining strength and uncertainty for preferences in the graph model for conflict resolution with multiple decision makers	THEORY AND DECISION			English	Article						Hybrid preferences; Strength of preference; Preference uncertainty; Decision analysis; Graph model for conflict resolution	STATUS-QUO ANALYSIS; SUPPORT-SYSTEM; ATTRIBUTE CONFLICT; EQUILIBRIA; GAMES	A hybrid preference framework is proposed for strategic conflict analysis to integrate preference strength and preference uncertainty into the paradigm of the graph model for conflict resolution (GMCR) under multiple decision makers. This structure offers decision makers a more flexible mechanism for preference expression, which can include strong or mild preference of one state or scenario over another, as well as equal preference. In addition, preference between two states can be uncertain. The result is a preference framework that is more general than existing models which consider preference strength and preference uncertainty separately. Within the hybrid preference structure, four kinds of stability are defined as solution concepts and a post-stability analysis, called status quo analysis, which can be used to track the evolution of a given conflict. Algorithms are provided for implementing the key inputs of stability analysis and status quo analysis within the extended preference structure. The new stability concepts under the hybrid preference structure can be used to model complex strategic conflicts arising in practical applications, and can provide new insights for the conflicts. The method is illustrated using the conflict over proposed bulk water exports from Lake Gisborne in Newfoundland, Canada.	[Xu, Haiyan; hipel, keith william] Univ Waterloo, Dept Syst Design Engn, Waterloo, ON N2L 3G1, Canada; [Kilgour, D. Marc] Wilfrid Laurier Univ, Dept Math, Waterloo, ON N2L 3C5, Ca