J	Dowlatabadi, N; Banihabib, ME; Roozbahani, A; Randhir, TO				Dowlatabadi, Nargeskhatoon; Banihabib, Mohammad Ebrahim; Roozbahani, Abbas; Randhir, Timothy O.			Enhanced GMCR model for resolving conflicts in a transboundary wetland	SCIENCE OF THE TOTAL ENVIRONMENT			English	Article						AHP; DEMATEL; Game theory; GMCR model; The Hawizeh/Hoor-Al-AzimWetland	HIERARCHICAL GRAPH MODEL; DECISION-SUPPORT-SYSTEM; FUZZY DEMATEL; GAME-THEORY; MANAGEMENT; RESOLUTION; ALLOCATION; PREFERENCE	This research proposes an enhanced Graph Model for Conflict Resolution (GMCR) with application to an international wetland. The integrated model enhances GMCR using the Analytical Hierarchy Process (AHP) and Decision-Making Trial and Evaluation Laboratory (DEMATEL) methods to extract the relative preferences of decision-makers in conflict resolution. The Hawizeh/Hoor-Al-Azim Wetland is facing increased dust storms in recent decades which are attributed to drying up of Mesopotamian wetlands, creating the potential for conflicts among riparian countries. The proposed integrated approach was applied in the Hawizeh/Hoor-Al-Azim Wetland fed by the Tigris and Karkheh Rivers. Turkey, Iran, Iraq, and Syria are located in the Tigris River basin, and the Karkheh River originates from the Zagros Mountains in western Iran. The results indicate that the achievement of an environmental balance depends on cooperation between Iran and Iraq to persuade Turkey to release the environmental flow to the wetland. Three strong equilibrium points were identified among 15 feasible states: (a) establishing a regional agreement among Iran, Iraq, and Turkey to reduce the effects of conflicts in the Hawizeh/Hoor-Al-Azim Wetland; (b) coalition of Iran and Iraq to motivate Turkey to reduce water withdrawal from the Tigris River; and finally, (c) exchanging water release for commodity market in Iran and Iraq for Turkey. In general, the economic cooperation among countries can be used as a negotiation tool to solve water conflicts in international wetlands. (C) 2020 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.	[Dowlatabadi, Nargeskhatoon; Banihabib, Mohammad Ebrahim; Roozbahani, Abbas] Univ Tehran, Dept Irrigat & Drainage Engn, Coll Aburaihan, Tehran, Iran; [Randhir, Timothy O.] Univ Massachusetts, Coll Nat Sci, Dept Environm Conservat, Amherst, MA 01003 USA	Banihabib, ME (corresponding author), Univ Tehran, Dept Irrigat & Drainage Engn, Coll Aburaihan, Tehran, Iran.	banihabib@ut.ac.ir	Roozbahani, Abbas/AAH-3466-2019; Randhir, Timothy/A-7145-2009	Roozbahani, Abbas/0000-0002-8458-4538; Randhir, Timothy/0000-0002-1084-9716			Abe T, 2020, MATH SOC SCI, V103, P69, DOI 10.1016/j.mathsocsci.2019.12.001; Ali A.A., 2012, J EARTH SCI GEOTECHN, V2, P53; Antonelli M, 2015, INT J WATER RESOUR D, V31, P326, DOI 10.1080/07900627.2015.1030496; Banihabib M., 2016, C WENM; Banihabib M., 2018, C DOKUZ; Bilgen A, 2018, NEW PERSPECT TURK, P125, DOI 10.1017/npt.2018.8; Cao H, 2015, SCI TOTAL ENVIRON, V502, P224, DOI 10.1016/j.scitotenv.2014.09.025; Daggupati P, 2017, SCI TOTAL ENVIRON, V580, P832, DOI 10.1016/j.scitotenv.2016.12.029; Datta D, 2015, SINGAPORE J TROP GEO, V36, P38, DOI 10.1111/sjtg.12092; Datta D, 2010, OCEAN COAST MANAGE, V53, P468, DOI 10.1016/j.ocecoaman.2010.06.007; Fang L, 1993, INTERACTIVE DECISION, V3; FANG LP, 1989, EUR J OPER RES, V41, P86, DOI 10.1016/0377-2217(89)90041-6; Fang LP, 2003, IEEE T SYST MAN CY C, V33, P56, DOI 10.1109/TSMCC.2003.809360; Faris M.R., 2016, ACAD J SCI, V6, P295; Fuladavand S., 2015, J WATER RES OCEAN SC, V4, P33; Gandhi S, 2016, INT J LOGIST-RES APP, V19, P537, DOI 10.1080/13675567.2016.1164126; Govindan K, 2015, EXPERT SYST APPL, V42, P7207, DOI 10.1016/j.eswa.2015.04.030; Gursoy S, 2010, FIELD CROP RES, V119, P260, DOI 10.1016/j.fcr.2010.07.016; Tzeng GH, 2007, EXPERT SYST APPL, V32, P1028, DOI 10.1016/j.eswa.2006.02.004; Hamouda L, 2006, APPL MATH COMPUT, V179, P314, DOI 10.1016/j.amc.2005.11.109; Hasan C., 2014, ARXIVPREPRINTARXIV14; He SW, 2017, J SYST SCI S