J	Wu, ZG; Xu, HY; Ke, GY				Wu, Zhenggao; Xu, Haiyan; Ke, Ginger Y.			The Strategy of Third-Party Mediation Based on the Option Prioritization in the Graph Model	JOURNAL OF SYSTEMS SCIENCE AND SYSTEMS ENGINEERING			English	Article						Graph Model for Conflict Resolution; third party; mediation; option prioritization; minimal adjustment	DECISION-SUPPORT-SYSTEM; CONFLICT; INTERVENTION; RESOLUTION	The resolution of real-world conflicts is often supported by third-party intervention (i.e., mediation). This paper proposes a possible mediation support in the form of a reverse optimization procedure under the framework of the Graph Model for Conflict Resolution (GMCR). The approach computes minimal priority adjustments of preference statements that are necessary to achieve a desired agreement. A mathematical model, based on the matrix form of GMCR, is developed to analyze this third-party mediation problem. Thereby, this study makes a first attempt to obtain option-based mediation strategies, which add comprehensiveness to the traditional state-based strategies, yet are easier to understand and hence more acceptable to the conflict participants. To illustrate the practicality, the proposed procedure is applied to a medical dispute between a patient and a hospital, with the aim to suggest changes in the ordering of preference statements that lead to a desired outcome.	[Wu, Zhenggao; Xu, Haiyan] Nanjing Univ Aeronaut & Astronaut, Coll Econ & Management, Nanjing 211106, Jiangsu, Peoples R China; [Ke, Ginger Y.] Mem Univ Newfoundland, Fac Business Adm, St John, NF A1B 3X5, Canada	Ke, GY (corresponding author), Mem Univ Newfoundland, Fac Business Adm, St John, NF A1B 3X5, Canada.	zhenggaowu@nuaa.edu.cn; xuhaiyan@nuaa.edu.cn; gke@mun.ca		Ke, Ginger/0000-0001-5951-0580	National Natural Science Foundation of ChinaNational Natural Science Foundation of China (NSFC) [71471087, 71071076, 61673209]	The authors appreciate financial support from the National Natural Science Foundation 