J	hamouda, luai; kilgour, d. marc; hipel, keith william				Hamouda, Luai; Kilgour, D. Marc; hipel, keith william			Strength of preference in graph models for multiple-decision-maker conflicts	APPLIED MATHEMATICS AND COMPUTATION			English	Article							SUPPORT-SYSTEM; UNCERTAINTY; RESOLUTION	Models of strength of preference are incorporated into the graph model for conflict resolution to study realistically multi-objective decision making situations in disputes with any finite number of participants. A decision maker's preference is expressed using a triplet of binary relations that allows preference of one state over another to be strong or weak, and also allows indifference. Four basic stability definitions used in the graph model to represent human behavior in conflicts are extended to the context of the new triplet preference structure, producing strong and weak stabilities. Theorems governing the relationships among standard, strong, and weak stabilities are presented. Finally, application of the new preference representation to an international water resource management conflict confirms the practical utility of the triplet structure and the significance of the strategic insights it can provide. (c) 2005 Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved.	Univ Waterloo, Dept Syst Design Engn, Waterloo, ON N2L 3G1, Canada; Lakes Environm Software Inc, Waterloo, ON N2L 3X2, Canada; Wilfrid Laurier Univ, Dept Math, Waterloo, ON N2L 3C5, Canada	hamouda, luai(corresponding author), Univ Waterloo, Dept Syst Design Engn, Waterloo, ON N2L 3G1, Canada.	lhamouda@engmail.uwaterloo.ca; mkilgour@wlu.ca; kwhipel@engmail.uwaterloo.ca					BELL DE, 1980, DECISION REGRET COMP; Ben-Haim Y, 2002, APPL MATH COMPUT, V126, P319, DOI 10.1016/S0096-3003(00)00161-2; Brams S.J, 1994, THEORY OF MOVES; BRAMS SJ, 1981, CONFLICT MANAG PEACE, V6, P39, DOI 10.1177/073889428100600103; DYER JS, 1982, MANAGE SCI, V28, P875, DOI 10.1287/mnsc.28.8.875; Fang L., 1993, INTERACTIVE DECISION; Fang LP, 2003, IEEE T SYST