J	hamouda, luai; hipel, keith william; kilgour, d. marc; Noakes, DJ; Fang, Liping; McDaniels, T				hamouda, luai; hipel, keith william; kilgour, d. marc; Noakes, DJ; Fang, Liping; McDaniels, T			The salmon aquaculture conflict in British Columbia: A graph model analysis	OCEAN & COASTAL MANAGEMENT			English	Article							DECISION-SUPPORT-SYSTEM	The strategic conflict over salmon aquaculture development in the province of British Columbia, Canada, is analyzed systematically using the graph model for conflict resolution. The decision support system GMCR II, which permits the graph model methodology to be conveniently implemented in practice, is used to model and analyze the strategic interaction of aquaculturists, environmental groups, First Nations, other stakeholders, and the provincial and federal governments. This study is timely because the controversial moratorium on the expansion of the salmon aquaculture industry was lifted recently, with the express purpose of fostering economic growth. Strategic insights gained from the graph model analyses demonstrate how difficult it will be to develop salmon aquaculture so as to balance multiple objectives including sustainability, shielding of the natural aquatic ecosystem, economic benefits, and social welfare for key stakeholders. (c) 2005 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.	Univ Waterloo, Dept Syst Design Engn, Waterloo, ON N2L 3G1, Canada; Lakes Environm Software Inc, Waterloo, ON N2L 3X2, Canada; Wilfrid Laurier Univ, Dept Math, Waterloo, ON N2L 3C5, Canada; Thompson Rivers Univ, Sch Adv Technol & Math, Kamloops, BC V2C 5N3, Canada; Ryerson Univ, Dept Mech & Ind Engn, Toronto, ON M5B 2K3, Canada; Univ British Columbia, Inst Resources & Environm, Sch Community & Reg Planning, Vancouver, BC V6T 1Z2, Canada	hamouda, luai(corresponding author), Univ Waterloo, Dept Syst Design Engn, Waterloo, ON N2L 3G1, Canada.	lhamouda@engmail.uwaterloo.ca					*BRIT COL ENV ASS, 1997, SALM AQ REV REP ENV; CONNELL S, 2004, REGULATING SALM