J	Kato, Y				Kato, Yukiko			State transition for de-escalation in the graph model for conflict resolution framework	JSIAM LETTERS			English	Article						conflict resolution; graph model for conflict resolution; de-escalation		This study discusses the analysis method for obtaining solutions that allow de-escalation in international conflicts within the framework of the Graph Model for Conflict Resolution. CD games, a conflict type in which two decision-makers can choose Cooperate (C) or Defect (D) strategies, are analyzed by examining the state transition and stability of decision makers with a focus on reachability. Based on the analysis, a new conceptual set is proposed, called 'de-escalation reachability,' which enables focused analysis on the conflict states while avoiding any influence of arbitrators' attributes.	[Kato, Yukiko] Tokyo Inst Technol, Meguro Ku, 2-12-1 Ookayama, Tokyo 1528550, Japan	Kato, Y (corresponding author), Tokyo Inst Technol, Meguro Ku, 2-12-1 Ookayama, Tokyo 1528550, Japan.	kato.y.bj@m.titech.ac.jp					Brams S, 1993, THEORY MOVES; Fraser N.M., 1984, CONFLICT ANAL MODELS; FRASER NM, 1979, IEEE T SYST MAN CYB, V9, P805, DOI 10.1109/TSMC.1979.4310131; FRASER NM, 1983, CONFLICT MANAG PEACE, V6, P1; Howard N., 1971, PARADOXES RATIONALIT; Inohara T, 2008, SYST ENG, V11, P343, DOI 10.1002/sys.20104; Inohara T, 2016, APPL MATH COMPUT, V274, P372, DOI 10.1016/j.amc.2015.11.020; Kennedy, 1999, 13 DAYS MEMOIR CUBAN; KILGOUR DM, 1987, AUTOMATICA, V23, P41, DOI 10.1016/0005-1098(87)90117-8; Munton Don, 2011, CUBAN MISSILE CRISIS; NASH JF, 1950, P NATL ACAD SCI USA, V36, P48, DOI 10.1073/pnas.36.1.48; Sorensen Theodore C., 1965, KENNEDY; Zagare FC, 2014, ECONOMIES, V2, P20, DOI 10.3390/economies2010020	15	0	0	0	0	JAPAN SOC INDUSTRIAL & APPLIED MATHEMATICS-JSIAM	TOKYO	JAPAN SOC INDUSTRIAL & APPLIED MATHEMATICS-JSIAM, TOKYO, 00000, JAPAN	1883-0609	1883-0617		JSIAM LETT	JSIAM Lett.		2021	13						60	63					4	Mathematics, Applied	Mathematics	WI8CA	WOS:0007085