J	Hu, KX; hipel, keith william; Fang, Liping				Hu, Kaixian; hipel, keith william; Fang, Liping			A conflict model for the international hazardous waste disposal dispute	JOURNAL OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS			English	Article						Hazardous waste dumping dispute; Graph model for conflict resolution; Multi-stage analysis; Attitude analysis; Ivory Coast	DECISION-SUPPORT-SYSTEM; GRAPH MODEL; RESOLUTION	A multi-stage conflict model is developed to analyze international hazardous waste disposal disputes. More specifically, the ongoing toxic waste conflicts are divided into two stages consisting of the dumping prevention and dispute resolution stages. The modeling and analyses, based on the methodology of graph model for conflict resolution (GMCR), are used in both stages in order to grasp the structure and implications of a given conflict from a strategic viewpoint. Furthermore, a specific case study is investigated for the Ivory Coast hazardous waste conflict. In addition to the stability analysis, sensitivity and attitude analyses are conducted to capture various strategic features of this type of complicated dispute. (C) 2009 Published by Elsevier B.V.	[Hu, Kaixian; hipel, keith william] Univ Waterloo, Dept Syst Design Engn, Waterloo, ON N2L 3G1, Canada; [Fang, Liping] Ryerson Univ, Dept Mech & Ind Engn, Toronto, ON M5B 2K3, Canada	hipel, keith william (corresponding author), Univ Waterloo, Dept Syst Design Engn, 200 Univ Ave W, Waterloo, ON N2L 3G1, Canada.	k2hu@engmail.uwaterloo.ca; kwhipel@uwaterloo.ca; lfang@ryerson.ca					[Anonymous], 1989, BAS CONV CONTR TRANS; Asante-Duah D. Kofi, 1998, INT TRADE HAZARDOUS; CLAPP Jennifer, 2001, TOXIC EXPORTS TRANSF; Fang L., 1993, INTERACTIVE DECISION; Fang LP, 2003, IEEE T SYST MAN CY C, V33, P42, DOI 10.1109/TSMCC.2003.809361; Fang LP, 2003, IEEE T SYST MAN CY C, V33, P56, DOI 10.1109/TSMCC.2003.809360; Fraser N.M., 1984, CONFLICT ANAL MODELS; Hipel K. W., 2005, Systems Engineering, V8, P211, DOI 10.1002/sys.20031; Howard N., 1971,