J	Xu, HY; kilgour, d. marc; hipel, keith william; McBean, EA				Xu, Haiyan; Kilgour, D. Marc; hipel, keith william; McBean, Edward A.			Theory and application of conflict resolution with hybrid preference in colored graphs	APPLIED MATHEMATICAL MODELLING			English	Article						Conflict resolution; Matrix representation; Graph model; Hybrid preference; Decision maker	DECISION-SUPPORT-SYSTEM; MODEL; MATRIX	An algebraic approach is proposed to calculate stabilities in a colored graph with hybrid preference. The algebraic approach establishes a hybrid framework for stability analysis by combining strength of preference and unknown preference. The hybrid system is more general than existing models, which consider preference strength and preference uncertainty separately. Within the hybrid preference structure, matrix representations of four basic stabilities in a colored graph are extended to include mild, strong, and uncertain preference and algorithms are developed to calculate efficiently the inputs essential to the stability definitions. A specific case study, including multiple decision makers and hybrid preference, is used to illustrate how the proposed method can be applied in practice. (C) 2012 Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved.	[Xu, Haiyan] Nanjing Univ Aeronaut & Astronaut, Coll Econ & Management, Nanjing 210016, Jiangsu, Peoples R China; [Xu, Haiyan; McBean, Edward A.] Univ Guelph, Coll Phys & Engn Sci, Guelph, ON N1G 2W1, Canada; [Kilgour, D. Marc] Wilfrid Laurier Univ, Dept Math, Waterloo, ON N2L 3C5, Canada; [hipel, keith william] Univ Waterloo, Dept Syst Design Engn, Waterloo, ON N2L 3G1, Canada	hipel, keith william (corresponding author), Univ Waterloo, Dept Syst Design Engn, Waterloo, ON N2L 3G1, Canada.	kwhipel@uwaterloo.ca	McBean, Edward/ABB-9732-2021		National Natural Science Foundation of China (NSFC)National Natural Science Foundation of China (NSFC) [71071076]; Natural Sciences and Engineering Research Council of Canada (NSERC)Natural Sciences and E