J	hipel, keith william; kilgour, d. marc; Fang, Liping; peng, xyj				hipel, keith william; kilgour, d. marc; Fang, Liping; peng, xyj			The decision support system GMCR in environmental conflict management	APPLIED MATHEMATICS AND COMPUTATION			English	Article							NEGOTIATION SUPPORT; EQUILIBRIA; MODELS	The graph model for conflict resolution is put forward as a unique decision technology for systematically studying strategic conflicts that can arise in environmental management and elsewhere. This flexible conflict resolution methodology has solid and realistic mathematical foundations which permit it to model strategic decisions accurately, forecast compromise solutions, and assist in assessing the political, economic, environmental, and social viability of alternative scenarios to resolving environmental conflicts. To permit practitioners to conveniently apply the graph model for conflict resolution to practical real-world conflict problems, a ne iv decision support system called GMCR II (Graph Model for Conflict Resolution II) is designed. To explain the basic structure of GMCR II and how it works in practice, this paper describes its use to model and analyze an international environmental management dispute that took place in North America. (C) Elsevier Science Inc., 1997.	UNIV WATERLOO,DEPT STAT & ACTUARIAL SCI,WATERLOO,ON N2L 3G1,CANADA; WILFRID LAURIER UNIV,DEPT MATH,WATERLOO,ON N2L 3C5,CANADA; RYERSON POLYTECH UNIV,DEPT MECH ENGN,TORONTO,ON M5B 2K3,CANADA	hipel, keith william (corresponding author), UNIV WATERLOO,DEPT SYST DESIGN ENGN,WATERLOO,ON N2L 3G1,CANADA.						Aho Alfred V., 1987, DATA STRUCTURES ALGO; ANGUS J, 1990, PORTABLE COMPUTING, V4, P56; ANSON RG, 1990, EUR J OPER RES, V46, P181, DOI 10.1016/0377-2217(90)90131-T; BENNETT P, 1994, GROUP DECIS NEGOT, V3, P351; BENNETT PG, 1992, 35 U STRATHC DEP MAN; BRAMS SJ, 1981, CONFLICT MANAG PEACE, V6, P39, DOI 10.1177/073889428100600103; CARROLL JE, 1983, ENV DIPLOMACY EXAMIN; DIBATTISTA G, 1993, ALGORITHM