J	Garcia, A; obeidi, amer; hipel, keith william				Garcia, Amanda; Obeidi, Amer; hipel, keith william			Two methodological perspectives on the Energy East Pipeline conflict	ENERGY POLICY			English	Article						Graph model for conflict resolution; Generalised metarationalities; Policy analysis	GRAPH MODEL; GENERALIZED METARATIONALITIES; PREFERENCE; STRENGTH	Two complementary approaches for identifying potential resolutions to a conflict are applied to a pipeline dispute in Canada to gain a range of valuable strategic insights as to how it can be resolved. More specifically, the controversy over the Energy East Pipeline for shipping bitumen from the Alberta oil sands for refining in Central and Eastern Canada as well as shipping overseas is investigated using the usual definitions for stability as well as the metarational tree methodology in which policies can be taken into account. As demonstrated by the case study, enhanced strategic insights can be garnered when the metarational tree approach is utilised for exploring conflict resolution within the confines of existing policy. The metarational tree procedure constitutes a useful expansion of the overall Graph Model for Conflict Resolution set of techniques for formally investigating real world disputes. (C) 2016 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.	[Garcia, Amanda; Obeidi, Amer; hipel, keith william] Univ Waterloo, Dept Syst Design Engn, Waterloo, ON N2L 3G1, Canada; [Obeidi, Amer] Univ Waterloo, Dept Management Sci, Waterloo, ON N2L 3G1, Canada	Garcia, A (corresponding author), Univ Waterloo, Dept Syst Design Engn, Waterloo, ON N2L 3G1, Canada.	a9garcia@uwaterloo.ca					Abul Bashar M, 2012, IEEE T FUZZY SYST, V20, P760, DOI 10.1109/TFUZZ.2012.2183603; Becklumb P., 2012, PIPELINES GOVT DECIS; Council of Canada, 2014, EN E WAT MEETS OIL; Denstedt S., 2014, REGULATORY APPROVALS, P83; Det Norst Veritas (Canada) Ltd, 2014, PIP SAF; Edelman Canada, TC EN E RES SYNTH; Enbridge Gas Inc, 2014, CUST UPD; Enbridge GazMetro Uni