J	Garcia, A; obeidi, amer; hipel, keith william				Garcia, Amanda; Obeidi, Amer; hipel, keith william			Inverse Engineering Preferences in the Graph Model for Conflict Resolution	IEEE TRANSACTIONS ON SYSTEMS MAN CYBERNETICS-SYSTEMS			English	Article						Analytical models; Stability criteria; Decision making; Law; Probabilistic logic; Decision-making; game theory; graph model for conflict resolution (Graph Model); inverse engineering		In this paper, algorithms for inverse engineering preferences based on observable behavior are developed. The algorithms are based on the most commonly used stability concepts in the graph model for conflict resolution methodology and function by reducing the set of possible preference rankings for each decision-maker (DM). The reduction is based on observable moves and counter-moves made by DMs. This procedure assists stakeholders in optimizing their own decision-making process based on information gathered about their opponents and can also be used to improve the modeling of strategic interactions. A simple case study is used to illustrate the applicability of the algorithms.	[Garcia, Amanda; hipel, keith william] Univ Waterloo, Dept Syst Design Engn, Waterloo, ON N2L 3G1, Canada; [Obeidi, Amer] Univ Waterloo, Dept Management Sci, Waterloo, ON N2L 3G1, Canada	Garcia, A (corresponding author), Univ Waterloo, Dept Syst Design Engn, Waterloo, ON N2L 3G1, Canada.	a9garcia@uwaterloo.ca			Natural Sciences and Engineering Research Council of CanadaNatural Sciences and Engineering Research Council of Canada (NSERC)CGIAR	This work was supported by the Natural Sciences and Engineering Research Council of Canada.	Bashar MA, 2016, IEEE T FUZZY SYST, V24, P765, DOI 10.1109/TFUZZ.2015.2446536; Ben-Haim Y, 2002, APPL MATH COMPUT, V126, P319, DOI 10.1016/S0096-3003(00)00161-2; Fang L., 1993, INTERACTIVE DECISION; Fraser N.M., 1984, CONFLICT ANAL MODELS; Garcia A, 2017, APPL MATH COMPUT, V311, P184, DOI 10.1016/j.amc.2017.05.016; Garcia A, 2018, APPL