J	kilgour, d. marc; hipel, keith william				kilgour, d. marc; hipel, keith william			The graph model for conflict resolution: Past, present, and future	GROUP DECISION AND NEGOTIATION			English	Article; Proceedings Paper	International Conference on Group Decision and Negotiation (GDN 2004)	2004	Banff, CANADA			Graph Model for Conflict Resolution; GMCR II; strategic conflict; stability; equilibrium; coalition analysis; status quo analysis	DECISION-SUPPORT-SYSTEM; PREFERENCE	The Graph Model for Conflict Resolution is a methodology for the modeling and analysis of strategic conflicts. An historical overview of the graph model is presented, including the basic modeling and analysis components of the methodology, the decision support system GMCR II that is now used to apply it, and the recent initiatives that are currently in various stages of development. The capacity of this simple, flexible system to provide advice to decision-makers facing strategic conflicts is emphasized throughout, and illustrated using a real-life groundwater contamination dispute.	Wilfrid Laurier Univ, Dept Math, Waterloo, ON N2L 3C5, Canada; Univ Waterloo, Dept Syst Design Engn, Waterloo, ON N2L 3G1, Canada	kilgour, d. marc (corresponding author), Wilfrid Laurier Univ, Dept Math, Waterloo, ON N2L 3C5, Canada.	mkilgour@wlu.ca; kwhipel@uwaterloo.ca					Brams S.J, 1994, THEORY OF MOVES; Fang L., 1993, INTERACTIVE DECISION; Fang LP, 2003, IEEE T SYST MAN CY C, V33, P42, DOI 10.1109/TSMCC.2003.809361; Fang LP, 2003, IEEE T SYST MAN CY C, V33, P56, DOI 10.1109/TSMCC.2003.809360; Fraser N.M., 1984, CONFLICT ANAL MODELS; Hamouda L, 2004, ENVIRON MANAGE, V34, P474, DOI 10.1007/s00267-004-0227-2; Hamouda L, 2004, GROUP DECIS NEGOT, V13, P449, DOI 10.1023/B:GRUP.0000045751.21207.35; Hipel KW, 1997, APPL MATH COMPUT, V83, P117, DOI 10.1016/S0096-3003(96)00170-1; HIPEL KW, 1990, INFORM DECIS TECHNOL, V16, P347; Hipel KW, 2001, IEEE T ENG MANAGE, V48, P358, DOI 10.1109/17.946535; HIPEL KW, 2002, ENCY LIFE SUP