J	Matbouli, YT; kilgour, d. marc; hipel, keith william				Matbouli, Yasser T.; Kilgour, D. Marc; hipel, keith william			ROBUSTNESS OF EQUILIBRIA IN THE GRAPH MODEL FOR CONFLICT RESOLUTION	JOURNAL OF SYSTEMS SCIENCE AND SYSTEMS ENGINEERING			English	Article						Robustness; equilibria; level of freedom; conflict evolution; graph model		A novel approach for assessing the robustness of an equilibrium in conflict resolution is presented. Roughly, an equilibrium is robust if it is resilient, or resistant to deviation. Robustness assessment is based on a new concept called Level of Freedom, which evaluates the relative freedom of a decision maker to escape an equilibrium. Resolutions of a conflict can be affected by changes in decision makers' preferences, which may destabilize an equilibrium, causing the conflict to evolve. Hence, a conflict may become long-term and thereby continue to evolve, even after reaching an equilibrium. The new robustness measure is used to rank equilibria based on robustness, to facilitate distinguishing equilibria that are relatively sustainable. An absolutely robust equilibrium is a special case in which the level of freedom is at an absolute minimum for each individual stability definition.	[Matbouli, Yasser T.] King Abdulaziz Univ, Dept Ind Engn, Rabigh, Saudi Arabia; [Matbouli, Yasser T.; Kilgour, D. Marc; hipel, keith william] Univ Waterloo, Dept Syst Design Engn, Waterloo, ON N2L 3G1, Canada; [Kilgour, D. Marc] Wilfrid Laurier Univ, Dept Math, Waterloo, ON N2L 3C5, Canada; [hipel, keith william] CIGI, Waterloo, ON N2L 6C2, Canada	Matbouli, YT (corresponding author), King Abdulaziz Univ, Dept Ind Engn, Rabigh, Saudi Arabia.	ymatbouli@uwaterloo.ca; mkilgour@wlu.ca; kwhipel@uwaterloo.ca	Matbouli, Yasser T/E-6290-2016	Matbouli, Yasser T/0000-0001-7215-7638			Abul Bashar M, 2012, IEEE T FUZZY SYST, V20, P760, DOI 10.1109/TFUZZ.2012.2183603; Al-Mutairi MS, 2008, J SYST SCI SYST ENG, V17, P257, DOI 10.1007/s11518-008-5088-4; Fang L., 1993, INTE