J	Yu, J; hipel, keith william; kilgour, d. marc; Fang, Liping; Yin, KD				Yu, Jing; hipel, keith william; Kilgour, D. Marc; Fang, Liping; Yin, Kedong			Graph Model Under Unknown and Fuzzy Preferences	IEEE TRANSACTIONS ON FUZZY SYSTEMS			English	Article						Analytical models; Uncertainty; Stability criteria; Decision making; Process control; Fuzzy sets; Fuzzy preference; graph model for conflict resolution (GMCR); stability definitions; unknown preference; water diversion conflict	DECISION-SUPPORT-SYSTEM; CONFLICT-RESOLUTION; ATTITUDES	A new hybrid preference framework of the graph model for conflict resolution (GMCR) is proposed which allows decision makers (DMs) having both unknown preference and fuzzy preference to be taken into account in conflict modeling and analysis. The novel hybrid preference structure provides DMs with a more flexible technique to express preference. It is capable of covering the unknown preference of one feasible state over another, as well as fuzzy preference. Moreover, within the new hybrid preference structure, four extension forms of unknown preference are defined for different fuzzy stability definitions. These stability definitions under the new hybrid preference can be employed to thoroughly investigate complex conflicts existing in practical applications, and can offer enhanced strategic insights regarding the conflicts. A specific real-world water diversion conflict occurring in China, which includes multiple DMs and hybrid preference, is utilized to investigate how the new hybrid preference framework of the GMCR can be conveniently applied in practice.	[Yu, Jing] Nanjing Univ Sci & Technol, Sch Econ & Management, Nanjing 210094, Peoples R China; [Yu, Jing] Jiangsu Ind Cluster Decis Making & Consulting Res, Nanjing 210094, Peoples R China; [Yu, Jing] Ctr Low Carbon Econ & Environm Policy Studies, Nanjing 210094, Peoples R China; [Yu, Jing] Ctr Int Econ & Trade Studies, Nanjing 210094, Peoples R China; [hipel, keith william] Univ 