J	Kinsara, RA; kilgour, d. marc; hipel, keith william				Kinsara, Rami A.; Kilgour, D. Marc; hipel, keith william			Inverse Approach to the Graph Model for Conflict Resolution	IEEE TRANSACTIONS ON SYSTEMS MAN CYBERNETICS-SYSTEMS			English	Article						Conflict resolution; graph model; inverse approach; negotiation	DECISION-SUPPORT-SYSTEM; PREFERENCE; STRENGTH	Systems methodologies to model third-party intervention in international conflicts are developed within the framework of the graph model for conflict resolution (GMCR). An inverse GMCR is introduced to utilize the GMCR as a negotiation tool by altering the procedure of the original framework. The methodologies presented give a better understanding of how decision makers (DMs) can be motivated to undertake certain actions within the conflict. Moreover, the inverse GMCR tackles the problem of specifying which preferences for DMs lead to a particular resolution, thereby making it easier for a mediator or other third party to influence the course of the conflict. The methodologies are applied to a real-world dispute, a complex water conflict in the Middle East.	[Kinsara, Rami A.] King Abdulaziz Univ, Dept Ind Engn, Jeddah 22254, Saudi Arabia; [Kinsara, Rami A.; Kilgour, D. Marc; hipel, keith william] Univ Waterloo, Dept Syst Design Engn, Waterloo, ON N2L 3G1, Canada; [Kilgour, D. Marc] Wilfrid Laurier Univ, Dept Math, Waterloo, ON N2L 3C5, Canada	Kinsara, RA (corresponding author), King Abdulaziz Univ, Dept Ind Engn, Jeddah 22254, Saudi Arabia.	rkinsara@uwaterloo.ca	Kinsara, Rami/Q-2663-2015	Kinsara, Rami/0000-0002-5311-2204			Abul Bashar M, 2012, IEEE T FUZZY SYST, V20, P760, DOI 10.1109/TFUZZ.2012.2183603; Akanda A., 2007, FLETCHER SCH J ISSUE, P1; Bercovitch J, 2006, INT INTERACT, V32, P329, DOI 10.1080/03050620601011024; Bercovitch Jacob, 2009, P 12 IEEE INT WORKSH, P1; Fang L., 1993, INTERACTIVE DECISION; FANG LP, 1989, EUR J OPER RES, V41, P86, DOI 10.1016/0377-2217(89)90041-6; Fang LP, 2003, IEEE T SYST MAN 