J	obeidi, amer; kilgour, d. marc; hipel, keith william				Obeidi, Amer; Kilgour, D. Marc; hipel, keith william			Perceptual Graph Model Systems	GROUP DECISION AND NEGOTIATION			English	Article						Graph Model for Conflict Resolution; Graph model system; Perceptual graph models; Possibility principle; Strategic conflict; Emotion	CONFLICT; EMOTION	Theoretical structures are developed to account for the impact of emotion and perception in strategic conflict. In particular, the possibility principle facilitates modeling the effects of emotions on future scenarios contemplated by decision makers, while perceptual graph models and the associated graph model system permit the decision makers to experience and view the conflict independently. These new theoretical advances expand current modeling capabilities, thereby furnishing realistic, descriptive models without exacting too great a cost in modeling complexity. Specifically, these developments enhance the applicability of the modeling algorithms within the Graph Model for Conflict Resolution to real-world disputes by integrating emotion and perception, common ingredients in almost all conflicts. To demonstrate that the new developments are practical, an illustrative application to a real-world conflict is presented.	[Obeidi, Amer] Univ Waterloo, Dept Management Sci, Fac Engn, Waterloo, ON N2L 3G1, Canada; [Kilgour, D. Marc] Wilfrid Laurier Univ, Dept Math, Waterloo, ON N2L 3C5, Canada; [hipel, keith william] Univ Waterloo, Dept Syst Design Engn, Fac Engn, Waterloo, ON N2L 3G1, Canada	obeidi, amer (corresponding author), Univ Waterloo, Dept Management Sci, Fac Engn, Waterloo, ON N2L 3G1, Canada.	aaobeidi@uwaterloo.ca; mkilgour@wlu.ca; kwhipel@uwaterloo.ca					Bechara A, 2005, GAME ECON BEHAV, V52, P336, DOI 10.1016/j.geb.2004.06.010; BENNETT PG, 1980, FUTURES, V12, P489, DOI 10.1016/0016-3287(80)90005-1; BENNETT PG, 1977, OMEGA-INT J MANAGE S, V5, P749, DOI 10.1016/0305-0483(77)90056-1; CADDY JF, 2001, CADDY REPORT LOBS