J	hipel, keith william; Walker, SB				hipel, keith william; walker, sean g. bernath			Conflict analysis in environmental management	ENVIRONMETRICS			English	Article						conflict analysis; environmental management; negotiation; game theory; Graph Model for Conflict Resolution	DECISION-SUPPORT-SYSTEM; MANAGING GLOBAL HAZARDS; STATUS-QUO ANALYSIS; GRAPH MODEL; WATER-RESOURCES; MATRIX REPRESENTATION; COALITION ANALYSIS; CLIMATE-CHANGE; DRAMA THEORY; PART II	A wide variety of formal conflict analysis models and their applications to environmental conflicts are examined and put into perspective. In particular, the history of game theoretic models for conflict as well as their use in mitigating or resolving environmental conflicts is studied. The models and problem types are categorized to allow for a better understanding of the contrasting areas of environmental conflict management. Finally, the Graph Model for Conflict Resolution (GMCR) is applied to a generic conflict between developers and environmentalists to illustrate the usefulness of GMCR in environmental applications. Copyright (C) 2010 John Wiley & Sons, Ltd.	[hipel, keith william; walker, sean g. bernath] Univ Waterloo, Fac Engn, Dept Syst Design Engn, Waterloo, ON N2L 3G1, Canada	hipel, keith william (corresponding author), Univ Waterloo, Fac Engn, Dept Syst Design Engn, Waterloo, ON N2L 3G1, Canada.	kwhipel@uwaterloo.ca					Al-Mutairi MS, 2008, J SYST SCI SYST ENG, V17, P257, DOI 10.1007/s11518-008-5088-4; Arrow KJ, 2003, GAME ECON BEHAV, V45, P15, DOI 10.1016/S0899-8256(03)00114-3; Bahn O, 2008, AUTOMATICA, V44, P1545, DOI 10.1016/j.automatica.2008.03.004; BARRETT S, 1994, OXFORD ECON PAP, V46, P878, DOI 10.1093/oep/46.Supplement_1.878; Ben-Haim Y, 2002, APPL MATH COMPUT, V126, P319, DOI 10.1016/S0096-3003(00)00161-2; Benchekroun H, 2003, J ECON DYN CONTROL, V27, P1237, DOI 10.1016/S0165-1889(02)00023-4; Benchekroun H, 2002, ECONOMICA, V69, P207, DOI 10.1111/1468-0335.00279; Bernard A, 2008, J ECON DYN CONT